    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1967-09-18T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1967-09-18T00:00:00-05:00" n="246"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d246">
                <head>246. Memorandum From the President’s Special Assistant (<persName
                        corresp="#p_RWW1" type="from">Rostow</persName>) to President <persName
                        corresp="#p_JLB1" type="to">Johnson</persName>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d246fn1">Source: Johnson Library, National
                        Security File, Country File, <gloss target="#t_USSR1">USSR</gloss>.
                        Secret.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1967-09-18">September 18, 1967</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Port Restrictions on Soviet Ships</item>
                </list>
                <p>When this question was put to you last May (Tab A),<note n="2" xml:id="d246fn2">
                        <ref target="#d214">Document 214</ref>.</note> your reaction was to hold it
                    “for the present.”</p>
                <p>The original idea was: <list>
                        <item>—To increase the number of American ports open to Soviet and Eastern
                            European ships from 12 to about 50;</item>
                        <item>—To provide for board and search on a spot-check basis (instead of the
                            present full coverage);</item>
                        <item>—To reduce advance notification from 30 days to 7.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>Nick Katzenbach, <persName corresp="#p_KFD1">Foy Kohler</persName> and others at
                    the State Department have looked at the problem again. They have come back
                    recommending we take only the third step—reducing advance notification to 7
                    days. The original 30-day requirement was a rule the State Department set up for
                    its own convenience in processing visas and export licenses for bunker fuel.
                    (The Coast Guard has never required more than 7 days advance notice for its
                    search and surveillance responsibility.)</p>
                <p>The change might result in a few more Soviet and Polish freighters calling at
                    U.S. ports, and this might increase the chances of labor union opposition and
                    political flak. However, easing the requirement would go a long way toward
                    quieting the Russians and preventing retaliation (which the Russians have
                    threatened) against our cruise-ship calls at <pb facs="0606" n="578"
                        xml:id="pg_578"/> Leningrad and Odessa. <persName corresp="#p_KAN1"
                        >Kosygin</persName> raised the matter personally with Ambassador <persName
                        corresp="#p_TLE1">Thompson</persName> a few months ago.</p>
                <p>Nick does not believe we need Congressional consultation—as it might actually
                    stir up the issue over a minor administrative change. We would advise interested
                    commercial shipping agents but not issue a press release. I recommend
                    approval.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_RWW1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Walt</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
                <postscript>
                    <p rend="flushleft">Approve<note n="3" xml:id="d246fn3">This option is checked.
                            Handwritten notations at the top of the memorandum read: “Mr.
                                <persName>N. Davis</persName> notified 9/18/67,” “<gloss
                                target="#t_SS1">S/S</gloss> notified,” and “telegram
                            cleared.”</note>
                    </p>
                    <p rend="flushleft">Disapprove</p>
                    <p rend="flushleft">Speak to me</p>
                </postscript>
            </div>
